{{Infobox Bilateral relations|Bangladesh-Israel|Bangladesh|Israel|filetype=svg}}
[[Bangladesh|'''Bangladesh''']] does not recognize [[Israel|'''Israel''']]<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.jpost.com/Opinion/Moving-Israel-from-Europe-to-Asia-388259|title = Moving Israel from Europe to Asia|last = |first = |date = |work = [[The Jerusalem Post]]|access-date = 29 January 2015}}</ref> But [[Israel]] was one of the first nations to recognize Bangladesh.<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.jta.org/1972/02/07/archive/israel-recognizes-bangladesh|title = Israel Recognizes Bangladesh|last = |first = |date = 7 February 1972|work = [[The Jerusalem Post]]|access-date = 29 January 2015}}</ref> Although Bangladesh rejected It has taken a similar stance to that of its fellow Muslim nations in calling for an end to Israel's occupation of the [[Palestinian territories]] and for the creation of an independent [[Palestinian state]]. Bangladesh is also the only nation to have a complete ban on trade (indirect and direct) with Israel even though both are members of the WTO.<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.timesofisrael.com/bangladesh-editor-gets-7-years-for-attempted-israel-trip/|title = Bangladesh editor gets 7 years for attempted Israel trip|last = Winer|first = Stuart|date = 9 January 2014|work = [[Times of Israel]]|access-date = 29 January 2015}}</ref>

[[Bangladeshi passport]] has restriction on traveling to Israel.<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/artikel.php?ID=337838|title = Grant: I<U+2019>ll have no issue with my Israeli passport|last = |first = |date = |work = ghanaweb.com|access-date = 29 January 2015}}</ref> As Bangladesh does not have any diplomatic relations with Israel, it is not permitted for Bangladeshis to travel to Israel using a Bangladesh passport, which brought about the arrest of journalist [[Salah Choudhury]].<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.timesofisrael.com/the-unfathomable-life-of-salah-uddin-shoaib-choudhury/|title = The unfathomable life of Salah Uddin Shoaib Choudhury|last = |first = |date = |work = [[Times of Israel]]|access-date = 29 January 2015}}</ref>

In the immediate aftermath of [[2006 Lebanon War]] Bangladesh offered to send battalions of its infantrymen to help with the UN peacekeeping force, however Israel rejected it stating Bangladesh does not recognise Israel.<ref name="cnn.com">{{cite news| url=http://www.cnn.com/2006/WORLD/meast/08/21/mideast.main/index.html | work=CNN | accessdate=April 2, 2010 | title=Israeli troops shoot Hezbollah militants}}</ref> Although Israel rejected the country's participation, Bangladesh and [[Nepal]] were the first countries whose troops reached the shores of South Lebanon whereas Western nations such as the original leader and top contributor, [[France]], delayed their deployment. Immediately after other UN peacekeepers arrived, Bangladeshi forces had to leave immediately, as they were considered not to be neutral in the conflict based on the fact of Bangladesh refusing to recognise Israel and a comment made by Bangladeshi Foreign Minister [[Morshed Khan]] who described Israel's retaliation as "[[state terrorism]]".<ref name="jpost.com">http://fr.jpost.com/servlet/Satellite?pagename=JPost/JPArticle/ShowFull&cid=1153291956137</ref>

